CS 4440 Product Requirements Document
Project Name: OS Arena
Subtitle: A Real-Time Operating System Simulator and Visualizer

1. Product Overview
OS Arena is an interactive educational simulator that makes core operating system concepts visible in real time. Instead of only reading about CPU scheduling, synchronization, deadlocks, memory allocation, and page replacement, users can build scenarios and watch the OS respond step by step.
The product is designed for classroom demonstration, technical explanation, and algorithm comparison. It gives users a visual dashboard where they can create processes, assign resources, allocate memory, simulate concurrent execution, and compare the outcomes of different OS algorithms.
The goal is to turn abstract OS theory into something visual, interactive, and memorable.

2. Situation
Operating system concepts are some of the hardest topics for students to fully understand because most system behavior happens invisibly. In class, topics like process scheduling, thread synchronization, deadlock handling, and virtual memory are often explained through notes, diagrams, and small examples, but students do not always get to see how all of them connect inside one system.
Most project ideas only focus on one OS concept at a time, such as sockets, threads, or scheduling. While those projects can work, they often feel narrow and do not show the bigger picture of how an operating system coordinates many components at once.
OS Arena solves this by combining several course topics into one interactive simulator that demonstrates how an operating system manages competing processes, shared resources, and memory under changing workloads.

3. Customers / Users
Primary users:
CS 3337 students
course instructor and teaching assistants
student project teams presenting OS concepts
Secondary users:
future students studying operating systems
interviewers or recruiters who want to see a technical systems project
anyone learning scheduling, deadlocks, or memory management visually

4. Problem Statement
Students can memorize OS algorithms without fully understanding how they behave in practice. Many concepts are difficult to explain because:
process state changes happen invisibly
scheduling decisions are hard to track in real time
synchronization issues like race conditions are hard to demonstrate clearly
deadlocks and unsafe states are easier to define than to visualize
memory allocation and page replacement are often taught as static diagrams rather than dynamic systems
A strong OS project should not only implement algorithms, but also show why those algorithms matter and what happens when the system is under pressure.

5. Target
Build a visual simulator that lets users:
create and run processes and threads
test multiple CPU scheduling algorithms
demonstrate synchronization with shared resources
detect or avoid deadlock using Banker’s Algorithm
visualize memory allocation and fragmentation
simulate virtual memory with page replacement policies
compare algorithm performance through metrics and charts
The project should be polished enough to impress classmates and the instructor, while still being realistic for a 4-person team.

6. Product Vision
OS Arena should feel like a live operating system laboratory. Users should be able to create scenarios, start a simulation, and immediately understand what the system is doing and why.
The experience should answer questions like:
Why did this process wait so long?
Why does Round Robin behave differently from FCFS?
What causes a deadlock?
Why does LRU often outperform FIFO?
How does memory fragmentation affect performance?
What changes when synchronization is turned on or off?

7. Product Goals
Primary goals
Demonstrate multiple OS concepts in one unified application
Make invisible system behavior visible
Allow side-by-side comparison of algorithms
Create a strong class presentation and demo experience
Secondary goals
Build something interview-worthy
Practice modular system design in a team setting
Produce a project that can be extended beyond the class requirements

8. Product Scope
In scope
process and thread simulation
CPU scheduling visualization
synchronization demonstration
deadlock prevention or detection
memory allocation mapping
virtual memory and page replacement
metrics dashboard
preset demo scenarios
polished UI for classroom presentation
Out of scope
building a real operating system kernel
direct hardware-level memory control
real CPU execution or kernel-level thread scheduling
full distributed systems simulation
production-grade operating system features like file systems, device drivers, or bootloading
OS Arena is a simulator, not a real OS.

9. Product Options Considered
Option 1: Narrow Single-Topic Tool
Build a project focused on one topic only, such as:
a CPU scheduling visualizer
a deadlock simulator
a page replacement simulator
a thread synchronization demo
Pros
easier to build
simpler testing
lower development risk
faster to finish
Cons
feels less ambitious
covers fewer class topics
less impressive in presentation
may look similar to projects from previous years

Option 2: Unified Operating System Simulator
Build one integrated simulator containing:
process management
CPU scheduling
synchronization
deadlock handling
memory management
virtual memory visualization
Pros
covers more course material
looks more advanced and original
much stronger visual demo
easier to divide among 4 team members by subsystem
highly memorable for class presentation
stronger for portfolios and interviews
Cons
more integration work
requires careful UI and architecture planning
more complex testing
risk of becoming too large without clear milestones

10. Proposal
The team should build Option 2: Unified Operating System Simulator.
This option best fits the course topics and gives the strongest presentation value. A complete simulator shows not just that the team can implement algorithms, but that the team understands how those algorithms interact inside one system. That makes the project more impressive than a single-topic demo.
Instead of presenting isolated concepts, OS Arena presents a full systems story:
processes arrive
the scheduler chooses what runs
threads compete for shared resources
unsafe allocation can create deadlock
memory fills up and fragments
page requests trigger replacements
performance changes depending on algorithm choice
That full flow is what makes the project stand out.

11. Product Name
OS Arena
Possible alternate names:
Kernel Vision
Process City
OS Lab Live
ScheduSim
Preferred final name: OS Arena

12. Platform
Recommended platform:
Desktop application using Python and PyQt
Alternative platform:
Web application using React frontend and Python Flask or Node backend
Recommended final choice:
Python + PyQt desktop app
Reason:
easier for simulation timing and event control
strong GUI support
fast development for a student team
easier offline demo in class
easier to build interactive visual components without worrying about server deployment

13. Core User Experience
A user opens OS Arena and can:
create a workload of processes
assign burst times, priorities, resources, and memory needs
choose a scheduling algorithm
enable or disable synchronization controls
allocate resources and observe safe or unsafe states
run memory allocation and page replacement simulations
compare metrics after the run
The system should support:
play
pause
reset
step-by-step execution
speed controls
scenario presets

14. Functional Requirements
14.1 Process and Thread Management
The system shall allow users to:
create processes with ID, arrival time, burst time, priority, memory requirement, and resource needs
optionally create multiple threads within a process
display process states:
New
Ready
Running
Waiting
Terminated
display thread states if thread mode is enabled
show queues visually
14.2 CPU Scheduling
The system shall support:
FCFS
SJF
Round Robin
Priority Scheduling
The system shall display:
execution order
ready queue behavior
context switches
Gantt chart
average waiting time
turnaround time
response time
CPU utilization
14.3 Synchronization
The system shall include at least one classic synchronization problem:
Producer-Consumer
Dining Philosophers
Readers-Writers
The system shall:
allow a no-lock scenario to demonstrate race conditions
allow synchronization using mutexes or semaphores
display blocked, active, and waiting threads
log resource access events
14.4 Deadlock / Banker’s Algorithm
The system shall:
allow processes to request multiple resources
maintain available, allocated, and maximum resource matrices
determine safe and unsafe states
block or deny unsafe requests when Banker’s Algorithm is enabled
visualize resource ownership and requests
display deadlock risk warnings
14.5 Main Memory Management
The system shall:
simulate memory partitions or blocks
allocate memory to processes
display free and occupied regions
show fragmentation
support strategies such as:
First Fit
Best Fit
Worst Fit
14.6 Virtual Memory / Page Replacement
The system shall:
simulate a page reference string
display memory frames
support page replacement algorithms:
FIFO
LRU
Optimal
show page hits and page faults
compare fault counts across policies
14.7 Analytics Dashboard
The system shall generate performance results such as:
average waiting time
average turnaround time
CPU utilization
total context switches
number of page faults
deadlocks detected or prevented
synchronization conflicts encountered
14.8 Preset Scenarios
The system shall include preset examples such as:
high CPU contention
memory pressure
deadlock-prone resource allocation
race condition demo
page thrashing scenario

15. Non-Functional Requirements
The application should respond smoothly during live simulation
The interface should be easy to understand during a class presentation
Visuals should be clean and readable from a classroom screen
Modules should be loosely coupled so 4 team members can work in parallel
The system should be stable enough for repeated demos without crashing
The project should run locally without requiring internet access
The codebase should be organized and documented for future extension

16. User Interface Requirements
Main dashboard should include:
Left panel
process creation form
algorithm selectors
resource configuration controls
simulation control buttons
Center panel
live process queue
