18. System Integrations
Because this is a simulator, most integrations are internal rather than external.
Required internal integrations
scheduling engine integrated with process manager
synchronization logic integrated with thread/resource manager
deadlock detection integrated with resource allocation engine
memory manager integrated with process creation
page replacement module integrated with virtual memory panel
analytics engine integrated with all modules
Optional external integrations
These are not required, but could be added later:
export to CSV or PDF
save/load scenario files
optional web deployment for remote demos

19. Key Features That Will Impress the Class
The features most likely to stand out during presentation are:
real-time Gantt chart animation
live switching between FCFS, RR, SJF, and Priority
showing a race condition, then fixing it with synchronization
creating an unsafe state and demonstrating Banker’s Algorithm blocking it
comparing FIFO vs LRU vs Optimal page replacement
showing memory fragmentation visually
generating end-of-run performance summaries
These features make the project feel alive instead of static.

20. Success Metrics
The project will be considered successful if:
all core modules work during a live presentation
users can compare at least 3 scheduling algorithms
at least 1 synchronization problem is demonstrated clearly
Banker’s Algorithm correctly identifies safe and unsafe states
at least 3 page replacement algorithms are implemented
memory allocation is visualized correctly
the demo clearly teaches OS concepts, not just displays numbers
the project is polished enough to feel like a real teaching tool

21. Risks and Mitigations
Risk 1: Too much scope
Mitigation:
finish scheduling, synchronization, and memory basics first
treat advanced UI polish as secondary until core logic works
Risk 2: Integration issues between team members
Mitigation:
define module interfaces early
agree on data structures before coding
hold regular integration checkpoints
Risk 3: UI becomes cluttered
Mitigation:
keep a modular layout
use tabs or views if needed
prioritize clarity over flashy visuals
Risk 4: Demo bugs during presentation
Mitigation:
prepare preset scenarios
include reset button and safe fallback demos
test each algorithm with known examples

