24. Minimum Viable Product
If time becomes limited, the MVP should include:
process creation
FCFS, RR, and Priority scheduling
one synchronization demo
Banker’s Algorithm or deadlock detection
memory map
FIFO and LRU page replacement
one integrated dashboard
This still delivers a strong final presentation.

25. Stretch Goals
If the group finishes early, add one or more of these:
Stretch Goal 1: Save and Load Scenarios
Users can save a custom workload and reopen it later for repeated testing.
Stretch Goal 2: Report Export
Generate a PDF or CSV summary of:
selected algorithms
performance metrics
deadlock outcomes
page fault results
Stretch Goal 3: Guided Tutorial Mode
A built-in walkthrough that explains each OS concept as the simulation runs.
Stretch Goal 4: Multilevel Queue Scheduling
Add a more advanced scheduler to show deeper OS understanding.
Stretch Goal 5: Process Dependency Graph
Visualize parent-child relationships and process dependencies.
Stretch Goal 6: Socket-Based Remote Viewer
Allow one machine to control the simulation and another to view it, tying back to sockets from class.
Stretch Goal 7: Thrashing Detection
Add a warning mode that detects excessive page faults and explains why the system is thrashing.
Stretch Goal 8: “What Went Wrong?” Mode
After a deadlock or race condition occurs, the app explains the cause and how a different algorithm or lock strategy would have prevented it.
Best stretch goals for presentation value:
Guided Tutorial Mode
Report Export
Socket-Based Remote Viewer
Thrashing Detection

26. Final Recommendation
OS Arena should be developed as a real-time interactive OS simulator with visual modules for scheduling, synchronization, deadlock handling, memory allocation, and virtual memory.
This project is the strongest choice because it:
covers many topics from the class list
looks impressive in a live demo
divides naturally across 4 group members
proves technical understanding
is memorable enough to stand out from typical student projects

27. One-Paragraph Proposal Summary
OS Arena is an interactive operating system simulator designed to visualize how processes, threads, resources, and memory are managed in real time. The application allows users to test CPU scheduling algorithms, demonstrate synchronization and race conditions, detect unsafe resource allocation with Banker’s Algorithm, visualize memory allocation and fragmentation, and compare virtual memory page replacement strategies. By combining several OS concepts into one polished dashboard, the project turns difficult theory into a live, understandable system and provides a strong, presentation-ready final project for CS 3337.

